{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775847185437,"sessionID":"ses_28742b66fffeq9vlTLRIjddm4f","part":{"id":"prt_d78bd983f001xKI3wPjik9GhsS","messageID":"msg_d78bd8c32001QDIt1gVjg2wK7C","sessionID":"ses_28742b66fffeq9vlTLRIjddm4f","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_504378e385624e4a92a91d13","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: This delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing the HTTP reverse proxy core in `pkg/router`.\n6: \n7: ## Base Specifications\n8: \n9: - **AR**: AR-009\n10: - **Module**: `pkg/router`\n11: - **Language**: Go\n12: - **Size**: M\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## Background\n17: \n18: The router module is responsible for routing HTTP requests to backend Sandbox services. This delta implements the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## Requirement: Proxy Core\n23: \n24: ### Scenario: Proxy HTTP requests to backend\n25: \n26: **GIVEN** an HTTP request to the router\n27: **WHEN** the request matches a configured route\n28: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to the appropriate backend service\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## Acceptance Criteria\n33: \n34: - [ ] HTTP proxy core functionality implemented\n35: - [ ] Route matching works correctly\n36: - [ ] Requests are forwarded to backend services\n\n(End of file - total 36 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心\n\n## Overview\n\nThis delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing the HTTP reverse proxy core in `pkg/router`.\n\n## Base Specifications\n\n- **AR**: AR-009\n- **Module**: `pkg/router`\n- **Language**: Go\n- **Size**: M\n\n---\n\n## Background\n\nThe router module is responsible for routing HTTP requests to backend Sandbox services. This delta implements the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775847185428,"end":1775847185436}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775847185468,"sessionID":"ses_28742b66fffeq9vlTLRIjddm4f","part":{"id":"prt_d78bd9c1d001VhDoG5AMSyBXuF","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d78bd8c32001QDIt1gVjg2wK7C","sessionID":"ses_28742b66fffeq9vlTLRIjddm4f","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":21659,"input":6659,"output":100,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":14900}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775847187485,"sessionID":"ses_28742b66fffeq9vlTLRIjddm4f","part":{"id":"prt_d78bda41a001e301DhJrLgQL4r","messageID":"msg_d78bd9c50001iUHpwgYRnK1P5j","sessionID":"ses_28742b66fffeq9vlTLRIjddm4f","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775847246395,"sessionID":"ses_28742b66fffeq9vlTLRIjddm4f","part":{"id":"prt_d78bdafde001mrleFLvNIQFtZI","messageID":"msg_d78bd9c50001iUHpwgYRnK1P5j","sessionID":"ses_28742b66fffeq9vlTLRIjddm4f","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_629ac7dd18034680a513b534","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Delta Spec: AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心\n\n## Overview\n\nThis delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing the HTTP reverse proxy core in `pkg/router`.\n\n## Base Specifications\n\n- **AR**: AR-009\n- **Module**: `pkg/router`\n- **Language**: Go\n- **Size**: M\n\n---\n\n## Background\n\nThe router module is responsible for routing HTTP requests to backend Sandbox services dynamically discovered from AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs. This delta implements the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality.\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Router Configuration\n\n### Scenario: Router loads configuration with defaults\n\n**GIVEN** a Router instance is created with no explicit configuration\n**WHEN** the router starts\n**THEN** it SHOULD use default values: listen address `:8080`, backend timeout `30s`, idle timeout `60s`, health check interval `10s`\n\n### Scenario: Router loads custom configuration\n\n**GIVEN** a Router instance is created with custom configuration\n**WHEN** the configuration specifies `listenAddress: \":9090\"`, `backendTimeout: \"60s\"`, `rateLimitEnabled: true`, `rateLimitRPS: 50`\n**THEN** the router SHOULD listen on port 9090, use 60s backend timeout, and enable rate limiting at 50 RPS\n\n### Scenario: Router watches specific namespaces\n\n**GIVEN** a Router configured with `watchNamespaces: [\"ns1\", \"ns2\"]`\n**WHEN** the router starts its informers\n**THEN** it SHOULD only watch AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs in namespaces \"ns1\" and \"ns2\"\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: HTTP Server Lifecycle\n\n### Scenario: Router starts HTTP server\n\n**GIVEN** a configured Router instance\n**WHEN** `Start()` is called\n**THEN** an HTTP server SHOULD start listening on the configured address\n**AND** the server SHOULD be ready to accept incoming requests\n\n### Scenario: Router graceful shutdown\n\n**GIVEN** a running Router with active connections\n**WHEN** `Shutdown()` is called with a context\n**THEN** the server SHOULD stop accepting new connections\n**AND** it SHOULD wait for in-flight requests to complete within the context timeout\n**AND** it SHOULD close all idle connections\n\n### Scenario: Router handles server startup error\n\n**GIVEN** a Router configured with an invalid address (e.g., unsupported port)\n**WHEN** `Start()` is called\n**THEN** it SHOULD return an error indicating the address is invalid or port is not accessible\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Endpoint Discovery from AgentRuntime CR\n\n### Scenario: Router discovers new AgentRuntime endpoint\n\n**GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime informer running\n**WHEN** a new AgentRuntime CR is created with `status.endpoint: \"http://10.0.0.1:8080\"` and `status.phase: Running`\n**THEN** the router SHOULD add the endpoint to its backend pool\n**AND** the endpoint SHOULD be available for routing\n\n### Scenario: Router removes deleted AgentRuntime endpoint\n\n**GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime endpoint in its backend pool\n**WHEN** the corresponding AgentRuntime CR is deleted\n**THEN** the router SHOULD remove the endpoint from the backend pool\n**AND** no new requests SHOULD be routed to that endpoint\n\n### Scenario: Router updates AgentRuntime endpoint on status change\n\n**GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime endpoint in its backend pool\n**WHEN** the AgentRuntime CR status is updated with a new endpoint address\n**THEN** the router SHOULD update the backend pool with the new endpoint\n**AND** existing connections to the old endpoint SHOULD be closed\n\n### Scenario: Router ignores non-running AgentRuntime\n\n**GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime informer\n**WHEN** an AgentRuntime CR is created with `status.phase: Pending`\n**THEN** the router SHOULD NOT add the endpoint to the backend pool\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Endpoint Discovery from CodeInterpreter CR\n\n### Scenario: Router discovers new CodeInterpreter endpoint\n\n**GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter informer running\n**WHEN** a new CodeInterpreter CR is created with `status.endpoint: \"http://10.0.0.2:8080\"` and `status.phase: Running`\n**THEN** the router SHOULD add the endpoint to its backend pool\n\n### Scenario: Router removes deleted CodeInterpreter endpoint\n\n**GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter endpoint in its backend pool\n**WHEN** the corresponding CodeInterpreter CR is deleted\n**THEN** the router SHOULD remove the endpoint from the backend pool\n\n### Scenario: Router updates CodeInterpreter endpoint on status change\n\n**GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter endpoint in its backend pool\n**WHEN** the CodeInterpreter CR status is updated with a new endpoint address\n**THEN** the router SHOULD update the backend pool with the new endpoint\n\n### Scenario: Router ignores non-running CodeInterpreter\n\n**GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter informer\n**WHEN** a CodeInterpreter CR is created with `status.phase: Failed`\n**THEN** the router SHOULD NOT add the endpoint to the backend pool\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Path-Based Routing\n\n### Scenario: Router routes request by path prefix\n\n**GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://backend-1:8080\" registered for path prefix `/agent/`\n**WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/agent/session-123`\n**THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend-1:8080/session-123`\n\n### Scenario: Router routes request to code interpreter path\n\n**GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://ci-1:8080\" registered for path `/code/`\n**WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/code/execute`\n**THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://ci-1:8080/execute`\n\n### Scenario: Router returns 404 for unmatched path\n\n**GIVEN** a router with configured routes\n**WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/unknown/path`\n**THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 404 response\n\n### Scenario: Router handles path with query parameters\n\n**GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://backend:8080\" registered for path `/api/`\n**WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/api/data?param=value`\n**THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend:8080/data?param=value`\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Header-Based Routing\n\n### Scenario: Router routes request by custom header\n\n**GIVEN** a router configured with header-based routing rule: header `X-Backend` maps to corresponding backend\n**AND** a backend pool with endpoint \"http://backend-a:8080\" for header value \"backend-a\"\n**WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `X-Backend: backend-a`\n**THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend-a:8080`\n\n### Scenario: Router routes request by content-type header\n\n**GIVEN** a router configured with header routing for `Content-Type`\n**AND** a backend pool with endpoint for JSON requests\n**WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `Content-Type: application/json`\n**THEN** the request SHOULD be routed to the appropriate backend\n\n### Scenario: Router falls back to default when header not matched\n\n**GIVEN** a router configured with header-based routing and a default backend\n**WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `X-Custom: unknown-value`\n**AND** no backend is configured for \"unknown-value\"\n**THEN** the request SHOULD be routed to the default backend\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Health Checking\n\n### Scenario: Router performs periodic health checks\n\n**GIVEN** a backend pool with endpoints\n**WHEN** the health check interval (default 10s) elapses\n**THEN** the router SHOULD send health check requests to each backend\n**AND** mark backends as healthy or unhealthy based on the response\n\n### Scenario: Router removes unhealthy backend from pool\n\n**GIVEN** a backend pool with a healthy endpoint\n**WHEN** the endpoint fails health checks for 3 consecutive attempts\n**THEN** the router SHOULD mark the backend as unhealthy\n**AND** stop routing requests to that backend\n\n### Scenario: Router adds recovered backend back to pool\n\n**GIVEN** a backend pool with an unhealthy endpoint\n**WHEN** the endpoint passes a health check\n**THEN** the router SHOULD mark the backend as healthy\n**AND** resume routing requests to that backend\n\n### Scenario: Health check timeout\n\n**GIVEN** a backend endpoint that does not respond\n**WHEN** a health check request times out (default 5s)\n**THEN** the backend SHOULD be marked as unhealthy\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Connection Pooling\n\n### Scenario: Router reuses connections to backends\n\n**GIVEN** a router with connection pooling enabled\n**WHEN** multiple requests are routed to the same backend\n**THEN** the router SHOULD reuse existing connections via HTTP keep-alive\n**AND** not create a new connection for each request\n\n### Scenario: Router limits connections per backend\n\n**GIVEN** a router configured with `maxConnsPerBackend: 100`\n**WHEN** more than 100 concurrent connections exist to a backend\n**THEN** the router SHOULD queue additional connection requests\n**OR** return an error indicating the backend is overloaded\n\n### Scenario: Router closes idle connections\n\n**GIVEN** a router with `idleTimeout: 60s`\n**WHEN** a connection to a backend has been idle for 60 seconds\n**THEN** the router SHOULD close the idle connection\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Rate Limiting\n\n### Scenario: Rate limiting restricts requests per client\n\n**GIVEN** a router with rate limiting enabled (`rateLimitRPS: 10`)\n**WHEN** a client sends 15 requests per second\n**THEN** the router SHOULD allow 10 requests through\n**AND** return HTTP 429 for the remaining 5 requests\n\n### Scenario: Rate limiting uses token bucket algorithm\n\n**GIVEN** a router with rate limiting enabled\n**WHEN** requests arrive at varying rates\n**THEN** the router SHOULD use token bucket algorithm for smooth rate limiting\n**AND** allow burst traffic up to the bucket size\n\n### Scenario: Rate limiting is disabled by default\n\n**GIVEN** a router with default configuration\n**WHEN** the router starts without explicit rate limit settings\n**THEN** rate limiting SHOULD NOT be active\n**AND** all requests SHOULD be processed normally\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Authentication Middleware\n\n### Scenario: Router validates authentication token\n\n**GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n**WHEN** a request arrives with valid `Authorization: Bearer <token>`\n**THEN** the request SHOULD be allowed through\n\n### Scenario: Router rejects unauthenticated request\n\n**GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n**WHEN** a request arrives without `Authorization` header\n**THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 401 response\n\n### Scenario: Router rejects invalid token\n\n**GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n**WHEN** a request arrives with invalid `Authorization: Bearer <invalid-token>`\n**THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 401 response\n\n### Scenario: Authentication is disabled by default\n\n**GIVEN** a router with default configuration\n**WHEN** the router starts without explicit auth settings\n**AND** a request arrives without authorization\n**THEN** the request SHOULD be allowed through\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Metrics\n\n### Scenario: Router exposes request latency metric\n\n**GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n**WHEN** a request is proxied to a backend\n**THEN** a Prometheus histogram `router_request_duration_seconds` SHOULD be recorded\n\n### Scenario: Router exposes backend request count metric\n\n**GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n**WHEN** requests are proxied to backends\n**THEN** a Prometheus counter `router_backend_requests_total` SHOULD be incremented per backend\n\n### Scenario: Router exposes backend health status metric\n\n**GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n**WHEN** backend health status changes\n**THEN** a Prometheus gauge `router_backend_healthy` SHOULD reflect the status (1=healthy, 0=unhealthy)\n\n### Scenario: Router exposes error rate metric\n\n**GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n**WHEN** a proxied request fails (backend error or timeout)\n**THEN** a Prometheus counter `router_errors_total` SHOULD be incremented\n\n---\n\n## Requirement: Request Logging\n\n### Scenario: Router logs incoming requests\n\n**GIVEN** a router with logging middleware active\n**WHEN** an HTTP request is received\n**THEN** the log SHOULD contain: method, path, client IP, timestamp\n\n### Scenario: Router logs proxied response status\n\n**GIVEN** a router with logging middleware active\n**WHEN** a proxied request completes\n**THEN** the log SHOULD contain: status code, response time, backend URL\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Router loads configuration with proper defaults\n- [ ] Router starts and listens on configured address\n- [ ] Router gracefully shuts down with active connections\n- [ ] Endpoints are discovered from AgentRuntime CRs with Running phase\n- [ ] Endpoints are removed when AgentRuntime CR is deleted\n- [ ] Endpoints are discovered from CodeInterpreter CRs with Running phase\n- [ ] Endpoints are removed when CodeInterpreter CR is deleted\n- [ ] Requests are routed based on path prefix\n- [ ] Requests are routed based on custom headers\n- [ ] 404 is returned for unmatched paths\n- [ ] Health checks run at configured intervals\n- [ ] Unhealthy backends are removed from routing pool\n- [ ] Healthy backends are restored after recovery\n- [ ] Connection pooling reuses HTTP connections\n- [ ] Connection limits per backend are enforced\n- [ ] Rate limiting restricts requests when enabled\n- [ ] Rate limiting allows requests when disabled\n- [ ] Authentication validates bearer tokens\n- [ ] Unauthenticated requests are rejected when auth enabled\n- [ ] Metrics are exported for Prometheus scraping\n- [ ] Request logs contain method, path, status, duration\n- [ ] Graceful shutdown completes within timeout","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md","exists":true,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775847246371,"end":1775847246391}}}}
